CONTEXT :

The purpose is to classify a given silhouette as one of three types of vehicle, using a set of features extracted from the silhouette. The vehicle may be viewed from one of many different angles.

DATA DESCRIPTION :

The data contains features extracted from the silhouette of vehicles in different angles. Four "Corgie" model vehicles were used for the experiment: a double decker bus, Cheverolet van, Saab 9000 and an Opel Manta 400 cars. This particular combination of vehicles was chosen with the expectation that the bus, van and either one of the cars would be readily distinguishable, but it would be more difficult to distinguish between the cars.

All the features are numeric i.e. geometric features extracted from the silhouette.

PROJECT OBJECTIVE :

Apply dimensionality reduction technique – PCA and train a model using principal components instead of training the model using just the raw data

  • Cars have relatively large compactness, Buses have lowest, 80 Vans have comapactness around 90, Cars are more likely to have distribution of compactness from 90-110.
  • Cars have circularity mostly at two peaks around 35-40 and other around 50-55, Buses come in the middle region around 40-45, Vans can only be seen around middle that is around 40-45
  • Cars have distance_circularity distribution likely towards 100-110, Buses are more likely to show circularity distribution around 40-45, The circularity for Vans vary around 35-50 and then decreases towards the end.
  • Cars have relatively two major distribution for distance_circularity one around 60-80 and other a bigger peak around 95-110, Buses's are distributed majorly around 60-80 nearly symmetrical and becomes almost parallel to the axis, Vans similar to the cars have a distribution around 60-70 and 80-90. *Radius Ratio for cars is likely to be higher as comapred for other vehicles, around 200. Vans show maximum radius _ratio around 140, distribution is almost symmetric in this region, Buses have almost equal distribution for radius ration around 120-200.
  • for pr_axis_aspect ratio distribution for cars is a sharp equal distribution around 60, for Vans it is similar in the 60 but buses seems to be dominating in two regions one around 40 and 70.
  • max_length_aspect_ratio for vans seems to be uniformly distributed with maximum occurance around 10, buses seems to be having a uniform distribution around maximum occurance of 5 and slightly higher count as compared to vans, Cars have relatively two peaks around 8 and 11.
  • Scatter raio is largest for cars around 210, Vans show 2 major distribution around 130 and 150 and a small peak around 120, Bus seems to be distributed with just one major peak around 150 and skewed towards right.
  • Elongatedness have a peak around 32 and data is mostly right skewed with a small bulk around 42, Buses have a peak in distribution around 45 and distribution is left oriented, Vans have a strong right skew, there is a strong peak around 44 and smaller consequitive peaks around 50 and 55.
  • px_axis_rectangularity for bus is mostly right skewed with peak around 19, Vans have 3 claer distribution around 18,19 and 20, Cars have two peaks around 19 and 24 and data seemsto be spread out.
  • max_length_rectangularity for buses is equally distributed around 145 and this is highest among all 3 vehicles.
  • scaled_variance is right skewed for bus , left skewed for cars and left skewed also for van. scaled_varaince_1 also followes a similar pattern to the scaled variance.scaled_radius_of_gyration for cars is distributed around two peaks 140 and 210, buses follow a similar distribution as comapred to the max_length_rectangularity, vans have left skewness and majority of data between 120 and 180.
  • scaled_radius_of_gyratron_1 for cars have a relatively larger peak as compared to vans and buses.
  • skewness_about is clearly right skewed for all 3 vehicles.
  • skewness_about_1 is similar to the skewness_about feature.
  • skewness_About_2 for cars have a strong distribution around 180 and data is right skewed for buses and vans. * hollow_ratio seems to be normally distributed for cars and right skewed for bus and vans.

from sklearn.decomposition import PCA

pca=PCA(n_components=10)
pca.fit(df_scaled); #Fitting the model

#Displaying Eigen values 
print('Eigen values: ',pca.explained_variance_,"\n")

#Displaying Eigen Vectors
print('Eigen Vectors: ',pca.components_,"\n")

#Dispalying % of variance explained by 5 components
print('Variance Explained :',pca.explained_variance_ratio_,"\n")


plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
plt.subplot(2,2,1)
ax1=sns.barplot(x=list(range(1,11)),y=pca.explained_variance_ratio_,)
ax1.set_xlabel('Eigen Vectors');
ax1.set_ylabel('Varaince')

plt.subplot(2,2,2)
plt.step(x=list(range(1,11)),y=np.cumsum(pca.explained_variance_ratio_,))
plt.xlabel('Eigen Vectors')
plt.ylabel('Cumalative Varaince Covererd')
plt.show()

# Making SVM Model based on newly reduced dimensions
X=df_scaled.copy() #Independent Variables
y=df['class'] #Target Variable

# Train_Test_Splitting data for further analysis
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
X_train1,X_test1,y_train1,y_test1=train_test_split(X,y,random_state=50,test_size=.3,shuffle=True)

#Import SVM Classifier
from sklearn import svm

#Choosing a Uniform gamma=0.025 and C=3
clf=svm.SVC(gamma=0.65,C=5);
clf.fit(X_train1,y_train1);
y_pred1=clf.predict(X_test1);

#Checking scores
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score,precision_score,recall_score,confusion_matrix,classification_report,f1_score

print('----------------------Classification Report------------------')
print("\n")
print(classification_report(y_test1,y_pred1))
print("Accuracy for original data----> ",accuracy_score(y_test1,y_pred1))
print("\n")

Conclusion

We come to state following conclusions :

  • Using the original data, The accuracy is around 89% for the SVM model.
  • By reducing dimensions to 5, we get accuracy around 78% for the same SVM model.
  • we can see the insample score for the Model which is around 9% more than the reduced dimensional data Model, This accuracy is however checked and more robust when we use the test data for our final model and it does not over fit the model since there is no co-relation remaining in the available new dimensions as compared to the original data set.
